[{"title":"Why Everyday Policing Deserves More Attention","slug":"why-everyday-policing-deserves-more-attention","date":"2026-06-08","category":"policing","excerpt":"Dramatic reforms make headlines, but most encounters between citizens and the police happen in routine, unremarkable moments.","content":"<p>Public debate about policing tends to focus on dramatic moments: high-profile operations, scandals, and sweeping reform announcements.</p><p>Most policing, however, happens in routine encounters. A complaint filed at a station desk, a checkpoint conversation, a patrol through a familiar neighbourhood. These small moments shape how citizens experience the state far more than any headline.</p><p>Taking the everyday seriously changes the questions we ask. Instead of only asking whether a reform passed, we can ask how it lands in practice, who it reaches, and what informal routines grow around it.</p><p>Future posts will pick up specific examples from research in South Asian cities.</p>","published":true,"image":""}]